---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../../../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import MadeByKaj from '../../../components/MadeByKaj.astro';

const basePath = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout
	title="Star clusters: families of stars | Learn | Found in Space"
	description="Stars are born in groups. Fly between real clusters — from stellar nurseries to ancient globulars — to see how age, gravity, and the galaxy shape stellar families."
>
	<SiteHeader section="Learn" />

	<main class="page">
		<!-- ── Intro (normal single-column) ────────── -->

		<section class="intro">
			<nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
				<a href={`${basePath}learn/`}>Learn</a>
				<span class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</span>
				<span>Star clusters</span>
			</nav>
			<p class="eyebrow">Learn</p>
			<h1>Star clusters: families of stars</h1>
			<p class="lede">
				Stars are almost never born alone. They form in groups — sometimes a few dozen,
				sometimes hundreds of thousands — from the same collapsing cloud of gas. What happens
				next depends on mass, density, and time. Some clusters dissolve within a few hundred
				million years. Others survive for longer than the Sun has existed.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="body-section prose">
			<h2>Why clusters matter</h2>
			<p>
				A star cluster is a natural laboratory. Every star in it shares the same age, the same
				initial composition, and roughly the same distance from us. The only variable is mass.
				That makes clusters uniquely valuable: they let astronomers isolate mass as the single
				factor that determines a star's brightness, colour, temperature, and lifespan.
			</p>
			<p>
				Clusters also trace the history of the galaxy. Young open clusters mark the spiral arms
				where star formation is happening now. Ancient globular clusters orbit in a halo around
				the disc, relics from the galaxy's earliest epochs.
			</p>

			<h2>Two families</h2>
			<p>
				<strong>Open clusters</strong> are loose, irregular groups of a few hundred to a few
				thousand stars. They live in the galactic disc, are typically young, and are only weakly
				bound by gravity. Given enough time, tidal forces from the galaxy pull them apart.
			</p>
			<p>
				<strong>Globular clusters</strong> are dense, spherical swarms of hundreds of thousands
				of stars. They orbit in the galactic halo, far from the disc. Most are ancient — 10 to
				13 billion years old, nearly as old as the universe itself.
			</p>
			<p>
				Scroll through the tour below to visit five clusters that trace the full arc from
				stellar birth to ancient survival.
			</p>
		</section>

		<!-- ── Tour zone (two-column scrollytelling) ── -->

		<div class="tour" data-cluster-tour>
			<div class="tour__chapters">
				<section class="tour__chapter" data-cluster="home">
					<p class="chapter-eyebrow">Home · 0 pc</p>
					<h2>The solar neighbourhood</h2>
					<p>
						We start at the Sun. The stars you see are the brightest within a few hundred
						parsecs — a tiny corner of the Milky Way's disc. From here, several of the
						galaxy's nearest clusters are within reach. Each one tells a different part
						of the story of how stars are born, live together, and eventually part ways.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="tour__chapter" data-cluster="orion-nebula">
					<p class="chapter-eyebrow">Star-forming region · ~400 pc · &lt;2 Myr</p>
					<h2>The Orion Nebula</h2>
					<p>
						The Orion Nebula is one of the closest active stellar nurseries — roughly
						400 parsecs away, visible to the naked eye as a fuzzy patch below Orion's belt.
						Inside it, stars are still forming. The cluster at its heart is less than two
						million years old.
					</p>
					<p>
						There is no clean shape yet. The stars are scattered through the nebula in an
						amorphous, chaotic distribution. The massive, hot Trapezium stars at the centre
						are ionising the gas around them, lighting the nebula from within. This is what
						every star cluster looks like at the very beginning.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="tour__chapter" data-cluster="upper-sco">
					<p class="chapter-eyebrow">OB association · ~145 pc · ~10 Myr</p>
					<h2>Upper Scorpius</h2>
					<p>
						At around 10 million years, the natal gas has been blown away by stellar winds
						and radiation. What remains is a group of young stars moving through space
						together — an <strong>OB association</strong>, named for the hot O- and B-type
						stars that dominate its luminosity.
					</p>
					<p>
						Upper Scorpius, part of the Scorpius–Centaurus complex, was never dense enough
						to be gravitationally bound. It is expanding, and will eventually dissolve into
						the general field population of the disc. Associations like this are not true
						clusters — they are the loosely connected aftermath of a star-forming event,
						caught in the brief window before they disperse.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="tour__chapter" data-cluster="pleiades">
					<p class="chapter-eyebrow">Young open cluster · ~135 pc · ~100 Myr</p>
					<h2>The Pleiades</h2>
					<p>
						The Pleiades — the Seven Sisters — are the archetype of an open cluster. At
						roughly 100 million years old and 135 parsecs away, they are compact enough
						to be striking to the naked eye: a tight knot of blue-white stars, still
						young and luminous.
					</p>
					<p>
						This is an open cluster in its prime. It has shed its natal gas but has not
						yet lost many members. The hot B-type stars that give it its distinctive colour
						are still on the main sequence. In another few hundred million years they will
						exhaust their hydrogen, and the cluster's appearance will change as its
						brightest members die.
					</p>
					<p>
						Open clusters like the Pleiades are the building blocks of the galactic disc.
						The Milky Way contains thousands of them, strung along the spiral arms where
						gas is dense enough for star formation.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="tour__chapter" data-cluster="hyades">
					<p class="chapter-eyebrow">Older open cluster · ~48 pc · ~680 Myr</p>
					<h2>The Hyades</h2>
					<p>
						The Hyades are the nearest open cluster to the Sun — only about 48 parsecs
						away. At roughly 680 million years old, they are well past their prime. The
						cluster is visibly more spread out than the Pleiades, and it is actively losing
						members: tidal forces from the galaxy are pulling stars away from the edges.
					</p>
					<p>
						No hot blue stars remain — they burned through their hydrogen hundreds of
						millions of years ago. The brightest stars left are orange giants. The
						<em>turn-off point</em> on the main sequence has moved to lower masses,
						and that shift is a direct clock: it tells you the cluster's age.
					</p>
					<p>
						In another billion years the Hyades will be unrecognisable as a cluster. Its
						stars will have scattered into the general disc population, just as the Sun's
						birth cluster did long ago.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="tour__chapter" data-cluster="omega-cen">
					<p class="chapter-eyebrow">Globular cluster · ~5.2 kpc · ~10 Gyr</p>
					<h2>Omega Centauri</h2>
					<p>
						Omega Centauri is the most massive globular cluster in the Milky Way — and
						it may not be a globular cluster at all. At roughly 5,200 parsecs, it contains
						around 10 million stars. Unlike most globulars, it has multiple stellar
						populations with different ages and chemical compositions.
					</p>
					<p>
						The leading theory is that Omega Centauri is the stripped nucleus of a dwarf
						galaxy that was absorbed by the Milky Way billions of years ago. Its outer
						stars were torn away; only the dense core survived.
					</p>
					<p>
						The flight here is long. That distance is the point — globular clusters orbit
						far from the disc, in a part of the galaxy that open clusters never reach.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="tour__chapter" data-cluster="home">
					<p class="chapter-eyebrow">Return · 0 pc</p>
					<h2>Back to the Sun</h2>
					<p>
						The journey back from Omega Centauri crosses thousands of parsecs of
						increasingly familiar space. Watch the local stars reappear as the Sun's
						neighbourhood comes back into view.
					</p>
					<p>
						From here you have visited every stage of the cluster lifecycle — from a
						turbulent stellar nursery to an ancient globular that may once have been a
						galaxy of its own. The same stars, the same physics, separated only by mass
						and time.
					</p>
				</section>

				<!-- spacer so the last chapter can scroll fully into the trigger zone -->
				<div class="tour__spacer" aria-hidden="true"></div>
			</div>

			<div class="tour__viewer-col">
				<div class="tour__viewer-sticky">
					<div class="tour__nav">
						<button type="button" class="cluster-nav-btn" data-cluster-fly="orion-nebula">Orion Nebula</button>
						<button type="button" class="cluster-nav-btn" data-cluster-fly="upper-sco">Upper Sco</button>
						<button type="button" class="cluster-nav-btn" data-cluster-fly="pleiades">Pleiades</button>
						<button type="button" class="cluster-nav-btn" data-cluster-fly="hyades">Hyades</button>
						<button type="button" class="cluster-nav-btn" data-cluster-fly="omega-cen">ω Cen</button>
					</div>
					<div class="viewer-shell" data-cluster-tour-shell></div>
					<span class="tour__status">
						<span data-cluster-tour-status>Loading…</span>
					</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- ── Exploration ideas (single-column) ───── -->

		<section class="explore-section">
			<h2>Things to try</h2>
			<div class="explore-grid">
				<article class="panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">Compare</p>
					<h3>Pleiades vs. Hyades</h3>
					<p>
						Fly between the two nearest open clusters. They are the same kind of object at
						different ages. Notice how the Hyades are more spread out and lack the bright
						blue stars that define the Pleiades. The Hyades are five times older.
					</p>
				</article>

				<article class="panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">Notice</p>
					<h3>The background changes</h3>
					<p>
						As you fly between clusters, watch how the background star field shifts. Nearby
						stars slide past quickly; distant stars barely move. The effect is strongest
						close to the galactic plane, where star density is highest.
					</p>
				</article>

				<article class="panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">Try this</p>
					<h3>Look back from Omega Centauri</h3>
					<p>
						After arriving at Omega Centauri, look back toward the Sun. You are now
						5,200 parsecs from home. The local open clusters — Pleiades, Hyades, Orion —
						are invisible specks. Globular clusters see the galaxy from the outside.
					</p>
				</article>

				<article class="panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">Key idea</p>
					<h3>Clusters as clocks</h3>
					<p>
						Because all stars in a cluster share the same age, the point where the main
						sequence turns off in an HR diagram directly encodes the cluster's age. Younger
						clusters have a higher turn-off; older clusters have lost their massive stars.
					</p>
				</article>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- ── Closing note ────────────────────────── -->

		<section class="closing-note">
			<div class="panel panel--accent">
				<p class="panel__eyebrow">Next lesson</p>
				<h3>See how clusters differ on the HR diagram</h3>
				<p>
					Each cluster you visited has a distinct population of stars — different ages,
					different masses, different turn-off points. The
					<a href={`${basePath}learn/topic/hr-diagram/`} class="link--gold">HR diagram lesson</a>
					lets you fly to these same clusters and plot their stars on a live
					Hertzsprung–Russell diagram. Watch how the main sequence shifts between a young
					cluster like the Pleiades and an old one like the Hyades — and see why
					astronomers call clusters "clocks written in starlight."
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<MadeByKaj />
	</main>
</Layout>

<script>
	import { mountClusterTourViewer } from '../../../scripts/cluster-tour-viewer.js';

	const mount = document.querySelector('[data-cluster-tour-shell]');
	const statusEl = document.querySelector('[data-cluster-tour-status]');
	const chapters = document.querySelectorAll('.tour__chapter[data-cluster]');
	const navButtons = document.querySelectorAll('[data-cluster-fly]');

	let currentCluster = null;
	let flyTo = null;
	let suppressObserver = false;
	let suppressTimer = null;

	function setActiveCluster(id) {
		if (id === currentCluster) return;
		currentCluster = id;

		chapters.forEach((ch) => {
			ch.classList.toggle('active', ch.dataset.cluster === id);
		});
		navButtons.forEach((btn) => {
			btn.classList.toggle('active', btn.dataset.clusterFly === id);
		});
	}

	// Suppress observer-driven fly-to briefly after a manual click,
	// so clicking a nav button doesn't get immediately overridden
	// by the observer firing on the current scroll position.
	function suppressObserverBriefly() {
		suppressObserver = true;
		clearTimeout(suppressTimer);
		suppressTimer = setTimeout(() => { suppressObserver = false; }, 1200);
	}

	// ── IntersectionObserver ──────────────────────────────────────────
	// Trigger band: top 30–40% of viewport. When a chapter's top edge
	// enters this band, we consider the user to be "reading" it.
	let goHome = null;

	const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
		if (suppressObserver || !flyTo) return;

		for (const entry of entries) {
			if (!entry.isIntersecting) continue;
			const id = entry.target.dataset.cluster;
			if (id && id !== currentCluster) {
				setActiveCluster(id);
				if (id === 'home') {
					goHome?.();
				} else {
					flyTo(id);
				}
			}
		}
	}, {
		rootMargin: '-25% 0px -65% 0px',
		threshold: 0,
	});

	chapters.forEach((ch) => observer.observe(ch));

	// ── Viewer mount ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
	if (mount) {
		mountClusterTourViewer(mount, {
			onStatus(msg) {
				if (statusEl) statusEl.textContent = msg;
			},
			onClusterChange(id) {
				setActiveCluster(id);
			},
		}).then((result) => {
			flyTo = result.flyTo;
			goHome = result.goHome;

			navButtons.forEach((btn) => {
				btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
					suppressObserverBriefly();
					setActiveCluster(btn.dataset.clusterFly);
					result.flyTo(btn.dataset.clusterFly);
				});
			});

			// Start with a gentle Sun orbit
			result.goHome();
			setActiveCluster('home');

			// If user has already scrolled to a cluster chapter, fly there instead
			for (const ch of chapters) {
				const rect = ch.getBoundingClientRect();
				const triggerTop = window.innerHeight * 0.25;
				const triggerBottom = window.innerHeight * 0.40;
				if (rect.top >= triggerTop && rect.top <= triggerBottom && ch.dataset.cluster !== 'home') {
					setActiveCluster(ch.dataset.cluster);
					result.flyTo(ch.dataset.cluster);
					break;
				}
			}
		}).catch((err) => {
			console.error('[website:cluster-tour]', err);
			if (statusEl) statusEl.textContent = err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err);
		});
	}
</script>

<script is:inline>
	(function () {
		var shell = document.querySelector('[data-cluster-tour-shell]');
		if (!shell) return;

		shell.addEventListener('touchmove', function (e) { e.preventDefault(); }, { passive: false });
		shell.addEventListener('touchstart', function (e) { e.stopPropagation(); }, { passive: true });

		var overViewer = false;
		var tour = document.querySelector('.tour');
		if (tour) {
			tour.addEventListener('mouseenter', function () { overViewer = true; });
			tour.addEventListener('mouseleave', function () { overViewer = false; });
		}

		document.addEventListener('keydown', function (e) {
			if (!overViewer) return;
			if (
				e.key === 'ArrowUp' || e.key === 'ArrowDown' ||
				e.key === 'ArrowLeft' || e.key === 'ArrowRight' ||
				e.key === ' '
			) {
				e.preventDefault();
			}
		});
	})();
</script>

<style>
	/* ── Page ──────────────────────────────────────── */

	.page {
		position: relative;
		min-height: 100vh;
		padding-top: 3.5rem;
	}

	/* ── Intro ─────────────────────────────────────── */

	.intro {
		max-width: 48rem;
		padding: 2rem 0 0;
	}

	h1,
	h2,
	h3 {
		margin: 0;
		font-weight: 600;
		letter-spacing: -0.03em;
	}

	h1 {
		font-size: clamp(2.4rem, 6vw, 4.2rem);
		line-height: 1.02;
		max-width: 18ch;
	}

	h2 {
		font-size: 1.55rem;
		line-height: 1.1;
		margin-bottom: 0.85rem;
		color: var(--fis-text);
	}

	h3 {
		font-size: 1.3rem;
		line-height: 1.15;
		margin-bottom: 0.65rem;
	}

	p {
		margin: 0;
		line-height: 1.75;
		color: var(--fis-text-soft);
	}

	p + p {
		margin-top: 1rem;
	}

	/* ── Body text ─────────────────────────────────── */

	.body-section {
		max-width: 48rem;
		padding: 2.5rem 0 1rem;
	}

	/* ── Tour zone ─────────────────────────────────── */

	.tour {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) minmax(340px, 52%);
		gap: 2.5rem;
		margin: 2rem 0 3rem;
		/* Break out of .page's max-width so the viewer column has room */
		margin-right: -1.5rem;
	}

	/* ── Chapters (left column) ───────────────────── */

	.tour__chapters {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
	}

	.tour__chapter {
		padding: 2rem 0;
		border-left: 3px solid transparent;
		padding-left: 1.5rem;
		transition: border-color 300ms ease;
	}

	.tour__chapter + .tour__chapter {
		border-top: 1px solid var(--fis-line);
	}

	.tour__chapter.active {
		border-left-color: var(--fis-gold);
	}

	.tour__chapter.active h2 {
		color: var(--fis-gold);
	}

	.chapter-eyebrow {
		font-family: var(--fis-font-ui);
		font-size: 0.78rem;
		font-weight: 600;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		letter-spacing: 0.08em;
		color: var(--fis-text-muted);
		margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
	}

	.tour__chapter h2 {
		transition: color 300ms ease;
	}

	.tour__spacer {
		min-height: 40vh;
	}

	/* ── Viewer (right column, sticky) ────────────── */

	.tour__viewer-col {
		position: relative;
	}

	.tour__viewer-sticky {
		position: sticky;
		top: 5.5rem;
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		gap: 0.5rem;
	}

	.viewer-shell {
		width: 100%;
		height: clamp(24rem, 56vh, 44rem);
		border-radius: var(--fis-radius);
		overflow: hidden;
		background:
			radial-gradient(circle at top, rgba(148, 220, 255, 0.08), transparent 20%),
			#02040b;
		touch-action: none;
		cursor: grab;
	}

	.viewer-shell:active {
		cursor: grabbing;
	}

	/* ── Cluster nav row ──────────────────────────── */

	.tour__nav {
		display: flex;
		gap: 0.35rem;
		flex-wrap: wrap;
	}

	.cluster-nav-btn {
		padding: 0.3rem 0.7rem;
		border: 1px solid var(--fis-line);
		border-radius: 999px;
		background: transparent;
		color: var(--fis-text-muted);
		font: inherit;
		font-size: 0.78rem;
		cursor: pointer;
		transition: border-color 120ms ease, color 120ms ease, background 120ms ease;
	}

	.cluster-nav-btn:hover {
		color: var(--fis-text);
		border-color: var(--fis-line-strong);
	}

	.cluster-nav-btn.active {
		border-color: var(--fis-gold-subtle);
		color: var(--fis-gold);
		background: rgba(242, 200, 121, 0.08);
	}

	.tour__status {
		font-size: 0.82rem;
		color: var(--fis-blue);
		padding: 0 0.25rem;
	}

	/* ── Explore section ──────────────────────────── */

	.explore-section {
		max-width: 48rem;
		padding: 1rem 0 0;
	}

	.explore-grid {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
		gap: 1rem;
		margin-top: 1.5rem;
		margin-bottom: 2rem;
	}

	.explore-grid h3 {
		color: var(--fis-text);
	}

	.explore-grid p {
		font-size: 0.96rem;
		line-height: 1.7;
	}

	/* ── Closing note ─────────────────────────────── */

	.closing-note {
		max-width: 48rem;
		margin-bottom: 2rem;
	}

	.closing-note h3 {
		margin: 0 0 0.65rem;
		font-size: 1.4rem;
		color: var(--fis-text);
	}

	.closing-note p {
		line-height: 1.75;
	}

	/* ── Responsive ───────────────────────────────── */

	@media (max-width: 960px) {
		.tour {
			grid-template-columns: 1fr;
			margin-right: 0;
		}

		.tour__viewer-sticky {
			position: relative;
			top: auto;
		}

		.tour__viewer-col {
			order: -1;
		}

		.viewer-shell {
			height: clamp(20rem, 45vh, 32rem);
		}

		.tour__chapter {
			border-left: none;
			padding-left: 0;
		}

		.tour__chapter.active {
			border-left: none;
		}

		.tour__spacer {
			min-height: 0;
			display: none;
		}

		.explore-grid {
			grid-template-columns: 1fr;
		}
	}

	@media (max-width: 720px) {
		.page {
			padding-top: 2.2rem;
		}

		h1 {
			font-size: clamp(2.2rem, 12vw, 3.6rem);
		}
	}
</style>
